The '''Carlsberg Fault zone''' is a concealed [[Tectonics|tectonic]] formation that runs across [[Copenhagen]] city centre.<ref name="nielsen-tybo-jorgensen">{{cite web|last1=Admin|accessdate=2018-05-02|title=Search|url=http://research.ku.dk/search/?pure=en/publications/integrated-seismic-interpretation-of-the-carlsberg-fault-zone-copenhagen-denmark(4fc002b0-74c3-11db-bee9-02004c4f4f50).html|date=26 April 2007}}</ref> It is one of the most significant [[Fault (geology)|fault]]s in the Copenhagen area<ref>"[http://www.geus.dk/DK/publications/geol-survey-dk-gl-bull/26/Documents/nr26_p41-44.pdf Efforts to include geological and geodetic observations in the assessment of earthquake activity in Denmark]". Søren Gregersen and Peter H. Voss, [[Geological Survey of Denmark and Greenland]]. Accessed 2 May 2018.</ref> and can be followed for about 30 km.<ref name="vandog">"[http://www.geus.dk/vand-og-data/baseline_hinsby_et_al_2003_limestone.pdf Copenhagen]". [[Geological Survey of Denmark and Greenland]]. Accessed 2 May 2018., [https://web.archive.org/web/20050330152419/http://www.geus.dk/vand-og-data/baseline_hinsby_et_al_2003_limestone.pdf backup]</ref>

The Carlsberg Fault is located in a NNW-SSE striking fault system in the border zone between the [[Danish Basin]] and the [[Baltic Shield]].<ref name="nielsen-tybo-jorgensen" /><ref>{{cite journal|title=High-resolution shear-wave seismics across the Carlsberg Fault zone south of Copenhagen — Implications for linking Mesozoic and late Pleistocene structures|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0040195116301792|journal=Tectonophysics|date=6 July 2016|issn=0040-1951|pages=56–64|volume=682|doi=10.1016/j.tecto.2016.05.043|first1=Janina|last1=Kammann|first2=Christian|last2=Hübscher|first3=Lars|last3=Ole Boldreel|first4=Lars|last4=Nielsen}}</ref> Recent earthquakes indicate that this area is tectonically active.<ref name="nielsen-tybo-jorgensen" />

It was described for the first time in 1925 at the [[Carlsberg Group|Carlsberg Breweries]].<ref name="vandog" />

